[The report above indicates that the outbreaks of chikungunya virus infections are expanding to new areas. Although the numbers of confirmed or suspected cases are not given in the report, comments by officials from the MoH indicate that the outbreaks are increasing in number. As of 8 Oct 2012, there were 500 suspected cases and 58 confirmed ones. Chikungunya virus is doubtless endemic in the Philippines, having caused sporadic outbreaks in 1954, 1956, 1968, and 1985 to 1986 (see ProMED-mail archive no 20120929.1315954), mainly in the center and south areas of the country. Since there is no commercially available vaccine, the only preventive measures are mosquito vector control and avoidance of mosquito bites.

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of the Philippines can be seen at http://healthmap.org/r/31D*. A map showing the provinces can be seen at http://mapsof.net/uploads/static-maps/philippines_regions_and_provinces.png. - Mod.TY]
